+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01Ts7ivMAd7J83jYHaUSKXnW","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The naive question that cracks this open: **\"Why can't I just try different orderings until one works best?\"**\n\nTaken seriously, this reveals that the scheduling problem is about **search strategy**. The fool's approach - try everything - is actually close to optimal for small inputs. For practical sizes, we need a smart ordering heuristic:\n\n1. Events with the most constraints (prerequisites, large attendee counts limiting room choices) should be placed first - they have the fewest valid positions\n2. Backtracking when a placement fails allows recovering from greedy mistakes\n3. The \"preferred room\" hint is just a tiebreaker, not a constraint\n\nThis is essentially a constraint satisfaction problem. The fool's insight: don't be clever about where to put things - be clever about what order to try placing them, and be willing to undo mistakes."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":142,"cache_read_input_tokens":19698,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":142},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9cfdc854-2020-4dc2-96ea-3a2820f1f9b8","uuid":"e5138d88-2d14-462b-9bb2-a7e189ea24f0"}
